501
00:25:25,525 --> 00:25:26,245
So I have a question.

502
00:25:26,385 --> 00:25:27,766
Your game obviously is multiplayer,

503
00:25:27,806 --> 00:25:29,147
which is the kind of game that already

504
00:25:29,507 --> 00:25:31,849
sort of encourages people to seek out a community.

505
00:25:32,129 --> 00:25:32,249
Yeah.

506
00:25:32,269 --> 00:25:33,190
So they have someone to play with.

507
00:25:34,931 --> 00:25:37,052
How viable would you say all of these things are

508
00:25:37,172 --> 00:25:38,954
sort of for a single player game

509
00:25:39,094 --> 00:25:41,435
that is generally more of a solitary experience?

510
00:25:41,595 --> 00:25:43,436
Well, yeah, I've thought about this as well.

511
00:25:44,322 --> 00:25:47,143
I think the key isn't necessarily single player versus multiplayer,

512
00:25:47,864 --> 00:25:51,366
but something that can be iterated on or have perpetual engagement.

513
00:25:51,606 --> 00:25:57,089
So a game like Darkest Dungeon, which has added content constantly,

514
00:25:57,449 --> 00:26:01,051
or like Don't Starve or whatnot, can easily foster this sort of community.

515
00:26:01,772 --> 00:26:05,494
A game that would probably not work well in this, like the most extreme case,

516
00:26:05,514 --> 00:26:07,535
would be something like a narrative game that's...

517
00:26:08,015 --> 00:26:09,858
like a short narrative game that's prone to spoilers.

518
00:26:10,338 --> 00:26:12,681
Because once the consumer finishes it,

519
00:26:12,721 --> 00:26:14,523
there's not much they can do beyond that.

520
00:26:15,104 --> 00:26:17,306
But if you have something that's like a systemic game

521
00:26:17,346 --> 00:26:18,668
that is procedurally generated

522
00:26:18,688 --> 00:26:20,069
or continues to build upon itself,

523
00:26:20,550 --> 00:26:22,953
there's lots of reasons for the player to come back

524
00:26:22,993 --> 00:26:23,734
and give you feedback.

525
00:26:25,155 --> 00:26:25,435
Thank you.

