563
00:27:58,599 --> 00:28:03,503
And then also being held accountable for the actions of those

564
00:28:03,823 --> 00:28:08,587
Individuals and occasionally having to apologize on their behalf, right? How do you?

565
00:28:10,969 --> 00:28:14,871
for one thing, incentivize a community,

566
00:28:14,891 --> 00:28:16,392
a type of community engagement

567
00:28:16,412 --> 00:28:19,975
that doesn't stratify your player base.

568
00:28:20,655 --> 00:28:24,718
And also, how do you hold people accountable

569
00:28:24,798 --> 00:28:27,980
without letting it get so far

570
00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:30,862
that you're stuck making an apology

571
00:28:30,922 --> 00:28:33,724
that you never should have been forced to make

572
00:28:33,744 --> 00:28:34,364
in the first place.

573
00:28:35,785 --> 00:28:40,327
So just to go over your question again, the first one is elitism, right?

574
00:28:40,908 --> 00:28:46,911
Yes, I guess the first one is how to prevent clicks among privileged players.

575
00:28:47,331 --> 00:28:52,874
And then the second one would be how to make those privileged players self-accountable

576
00:28:53,454 --> 00:28:56,416
so that you're not having to shepherd them around.

577
00:28:56,436 --> 00:28:59,838
Right, so these situations have already come to us.

578
00:29:01,642 --> 00:29:03,804
there have been complaints from other members

579
00:29:03,864 --> 00:29:05,005
who are not moderators,

580
00:29:05,265 --> 00:29:08,187
who felt like the moderators themselves were too click-like.

581
00:29:09,348 --> 00:29:10,469
The question, sorry,

582
00:29:10,549 --> 00:29:12,270
the question is that how do you prevent clicks

583
00:29:12,690 --> 00:29:14,752
and how do you hold players accountable

584
00:29:14,812 --> 00:29:17,133
for if they're in a position of power and they abuse it

585
00:29:17,213 --> 00:29:18,594
or something along those lines, right?

586
00:29:19,195 --> 00:29:20,776
So both have happened to us.

587
00:29:22,077 --> 00:29:24,198
As far as clicks are concerned,

588
00:29:24,839 --> 00:29:27,661
I've never done anything to actively prevent them

589
00:29:27,761 --> 00:29:28,501
in the sense that,

590
00:29:30,694 --> 00:29:37,819
I don't say, the moderators themselves do have a private channel for which they talk

591
00:29:37,859 --> 00:29:38,600
about moderation.

592
00:29:39,120 --> 00:29:40,421
And that in and of itself is a click.

593
00:29:40,461 --> 00:29:42,523
And they talk about their own things in private.

594
00:29:44,204 --> 00:29:46,846
I don't feel that this is destructive to the community.

595
00:29:48,447 --> 00:29:52,610
And I think a big part of that is a lot of what has gone into selecting the moderators

596
00:29:52,651 --> 00:29:56,954
themselves is to make sure that even though they have their own subsection of which they're

597
00:29:57,514 --> 00:29:58,435
essentially the elites.

598
00:29:59,425 --> 00:30:02,027
they're vetted so that they're not elitists.

599
00:30:02,207 --> 00:30:05,250
They do talk directly to everyone else as individuals,

600
00:30:05,330 --> 00:30:08,832
and I've established a rule page for the moderators

601
00:30:08,972 --> 00:30:11,894
to know that they should not talk to individuals

602
00:30:11,974 --> 00:30:13,295
as if they are inferior to them.

603
00:30:13,996 --> 00:30:15,677
Now, in the event that this does happen,

604
00:30:15,717 --> 00:30:17,358
and it has happened, we've...

605
00:30:19,160 --> 00:30:22,081
The developers are the highest tier of elites,

606
00:30:22,361 --> 00:30:24,582
essentially, in development, and they have to step in,

607
00:30:25,123 --> 00:30:26,583
which takes time off on our hands.

608
00:30:27,224 --> 00:30:29,025
It has happened a few times over the year,

609
00:30:29,465 --> 00:30:32,006
where we have to step in and talk to a moderator directly,

610
00:30:32,567 --> 00:30:33,227
and then guide them.

611
00:30:33,407 --> 00:30:35,348
But this particular correction process

612
00:30:36,749 --> 00:30:38,850
allows it, sort of,

613
00:30:40,351 --> 00:30:44,553
serves as a way of showing the moderators how to behave.

